ffected by different monetary regimes, the sources of its success and failure, and the factors that lead states to turn to its use. Kirshner thus succeeds in developing a generalized framework for the analysis of an important yet neglected form of state power that is likely to be of increasing importance in the post-Cold War era. Although some distinguished scholars have touched on the issue of monetary power, there has been until now no standard text on the subject. Integrating security studies and international political economy, this book is a timely synthesis that will be important to the entire discipline of international relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInternational economic relations. 0aMoney. 0aPower (Social sciences) 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aWorld politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAgadir crisis.  aAustria-Hungary.  aBandwagoning.  aBretton Woods.  aBush Administration.  aCzechoslovakia.  aDawes plan.  aFederal Reserve (U.S.).  aGerman question.  aGreat Britain.  aHoffmann, Stanley.  aHungary.  aInflation.  aInternational Monetary Fund.  aJordan.  aKeita, Modibo.  aKunz, Diane.  aLatin Monetary Union.  aLeague of Nations.  aMonroe Doctrine.  aMozambique.  aNasser, Gamal Abdel.  aOrganization of African Unity.  aPanama.  aPeloponnesian War.  aPortugal.  aQuesnay, Pierre.  aRist, Charles.  aSchacht, Hjalmar.  aSignaling.  aSoviet Union.  aSuez crisis.  aappreciation.  abimetallism.  aboatrocking.  acold war.  acurrency manipulation.  adevaluation.  adollar system.  aenforcement.  aentrapment.  aexpulsion.  aextraction.  afinancial diplomacy.  agold-exchange standard.  akey currency.  alocarno, treaty of.  amilitary currencies.  apurchasing power pari